english:
  title: Preface to the Complete Works of the Jimsan Lineage
  author: Choi Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When heaven and earth first opened and mountains rose to touch the sky, their pristine essence gathered in those heights, and there inevitably appeared men of exceptional talent and noble spirit. Some made their mark through virtue and achievement, others through literary excellence, their names ringing through the ages and standing tall for generations. Such were Shenbo and Zhongshan Fu of Mount Song, and Su Shi and Su Zhe of Mount Mei. Yet it is rare indeed for one person to embody all these gifts, rarer still for successive generations to carry forward such brilliance.

    Our Eastern Land possesses mountains and waters of surpassing beauty, supreme beneath heaven. And among our mountains, Jimsan rises in the southern highlands, magnificent and extraordinary, its peaks unrivaled in all the realm. Where divine spirits descend, there too descend men of rare genius. Thus it is no marvel that virtue, achievement, and literary grace flow continuously through generations, each passing the torch of brilliance to the next.

    One day, the Lord of Jimsan, Master Kang, brought to me a single volume—the Complete Works of the Jimsan Lineage—and requested that I write this preface. I humbly read it three times through, and what I found was like ice emerging from a mountain ravine, like pearls rolling across a lacquered tray, like the ringing of an ancient bell resonating through the air, like refined metal gleaming in sunlight. How extraordinary—three generations, yet as if all sprung from a single brushstroke!

    I never had the fortune to meet Tongjeong, though I have often sat with Wanyeokjae in learned discourse. With Injae, I have long counted myself among his companions. Now, observing these writings, I find the same austere elegance, the same serene simplicity in tone that I have known in their speech and bearing. Who would dare say that literature exists apart from the heart? That it does not have its roots therein?

    These descendants of noble houses, heirs to generations of high station and refined living, possessed from birth an elevated nature untouched by the corruption of worldly entanglement. Ice-like in their integrity, they took the Classics as their inheritance, gathering the nectar of wisdom, striking gold and jade with their words. They forged a unique mastery, ascending far beyond the common horde. And yet this excellence only deepened with each generation, as father and son illumined one another, and their household virtue grew ever more lustrous and admired. Truly, their names rival the mountains themselves in claiming heights within the universe. Is it not fitting, then, to call this work the Complete Works of the Jimsan Lineage?

    Thus I am convinced that the very lifeblood of literature flows with the cosmic force itself, drawing sustenance from the spirits of mountains—nothing mere chance or happenstance. As for their achievements and virtues, the official histories already record them, and I have no need to elaborate.

    Alas, the son of a master bowyer naturally becomes skilled in the craft of sieve-making, for the trade settles into his hands through custom. The offspring of swift horses are born to surpass their mothers, for their nature is the same. How much more so, then, when one inherits the refined essence of ages past and is schooled in ancestral teachings? The perfection of their literary art flows ever more wondrous and extraordinary, transcending the ordinary—this is the natural order, not mere fortune.

    Moreover, my bond with Jimsan grows ever deeper—we are allies, colleagues, friends who transcend the bounds of age and formality. His virtue and literary grace shine ever brighter, and these are what I most deeply revere. With diligent care he has gathered the scattered remnants of earlier works, bringing forth the brilliance of the past. Those who would compile future anthologies of letters will find in this a reliable testament. This is greatly to be praised.

    Therefore, I do not hesitate to append these humble words to the end of his work, following the old saying of the fly that clings to the tail of the swift horse.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Shenbo and Zhongshan Fu: Historical figures associated with Mount Song, known for their virtue and statecraft in ancient China'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Su Shi and Su Zhe: The renowned Song Dynasty poet-officials Su Dongpo (Su Shi) and his brother Su Zhe, associated with Mount Mei'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Tongjeong, Wanyeokjae, Injae: Likely courtesy names of predecessors in the Jimsan family lineage, representing earlier generations whose literary and moral excellence the author acknowledges'
  - key: ''
    value: The closing reference to the fly clinging to the swift horse's tail is a traditional Chinese metaphor for one's modest contribution gaining prominence through association with greater works
